public class SAT
extends BaseProblem
implements StartingConfigurationProblem, RandomConfigurationProblem, GlobalSearchProblem

Boolean satisfiability problem.

Satisfiability is the problem of determining if the variables of a given Boolean formula can be assigned in such a way as to make the formula evaluate to TRUE.

Constructor Detail

SAT

public SAT(java.io.File configFile)
    throws java.io.IOException,
           ProblemFormatException
Creates SAT from file.

Ignores lines beginning with 'c'. Requires configuration line (beginning with 'p') in format 'p cnf X Y' where X is number of variables, Y is number of clauses in formula. Optional weight line (beginning with 'w') in format 'w X1 X2 X3 X4..Xn", where n is number of variables. Assigns weight to each variable

Then expects list of clauses. Each clause contains several numbers, indicating index of variable (starting with 1!). Negative number means negated variable. Each clause ends with zero (new line is not required. Clauses must be after configuration and weight line.

Parameters:
configFile - input file to load data from
Throws:
java.io.IOException - if problem loading file occurs
ProblemFormatException - if line format is invalid

public SATIterator getOperationIterator(Configuration configuration)
Description copied from interface: Problem
Returns iterator for operations which are allowed for supplied attributes.

This iterator should be lazy initialized! If not, you are running into risk of performance problems (some algorithms creates lots of configurations and asks operationIterator for all of them).
